{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0c23085f-c565-4457-afb4-f0e0122f5212","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Expensive `**\\*.*` glob (line 9 of `.csproj`)**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA recursive wildcard glob over the entire project tree is evaluated on **every** build. It forces MSBuild to walk the full directory tree, which gets slower as the repo grows. Only include what you actually need (e.g., specific extensions or subdirectories).\n\n### 2. **File I/O via property function (line 13)**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during **evaluation** is a blocking I/O call that runs before any targets execute. This bypasses MSBuild's caching and runs every evaluation. If you need file content, read it in a target at build time instead.\n\n### 3. **3-deep chained `<Import>` (level1 → level2 → level3)**\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import is resolved and parsed during evaluation. While three levels isn't catastrophic on its own, deeply nested import chains add cumulative overhead and make evaluation harder to cache. Flatten where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** The `**\\*.*` glob and the `ReadAllText` property function are the biggest offenders — both perform real I/O during evaluation. The import chain is a minor concern by comparison.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"25323e69-f87f-4525-8667-6bfb8dea53b1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":431},"id":"9728dcbd-ccaf-4520-8d84-1bffc4f3f26b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:07:33.090Z","parentId":"76c5559b-54de-42c2-80dc-846b68e980e6"}
